To achieve this, we'll need to make use of both the main process and the renderer process in Electron. Here's an updated version of the code with the functionality added:

`main.js`:
```javascript
const { app, BrowserWindow, ipcMain } = require('electron');
const path = require('path');

function createWindow() {
  const win = new BrowserWindow({
    width: 800,
    height: 600,
    webPreferences: {
      nodeIntegration: true,
      preload: path.join(__dirname, 'preload.js')
    }
  });

  win.loadFile('index.html');
}

app.whenReady().then(createWindow);

ipcMain.on('message', (event, message) => {
  // Handle the received message from the renderer process
  console.log('Received message:', message);
  // You can perform any additional logic here, like sending the message to other users or storing it in a database
});
```

`preload.js`:
```javascript
const { ipcRenderer } = require('electron');

window.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  const sendButton = document.getElementById('sendButton');
  const messageInput = document.getElementById('messageInput');

  sendButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
    const message = messageInput.value;
    ipcRenderer.send('message', message);
    messageInput.value = '';
  });
});
```

As you can see, we've added an event listener in the main process to handle the received message from the renderer process. When a message is sent from the renderer process via the `ipcRenderer.send()` method, it triggers the `message` event in the main process, and the message is logged to the console. This is just a basic example, and you can modify and expand on this functionality as per your requirements.

