The code you provided seems to be iterating through each letter of the message and appending it to the `innerText` property of the `aiMessageElement` using a `setTimeout` function with a delay of 50 milliseconds between each iteration. The problem with this approach is that it treats spaces the same as any other character, so they are not being added to the `innerText` property.

One solution to this problem is to check for spaces and add them to the `innerText` property separately. Here's an updated version of the code that should fix the issue:

```js
let message = data.choices[0].message.content;
let words = message.split(' ');
let first = true;

for (let i = 0; i < words.length; i++) {
  let letters = words[i].split('');

  for (let j = 0; j < letters.length; j++) {
    setTimeout(() => {
      if (first) {
        aiMessageElement.innerText = letters[j];
        first = false;
      } else aiMessageElement.innerText += letters[j];
    }, 50 * (i * words.length + j));
  };

  if (i < words.length - 1) {
    setTimeout(() => {
      aiMessageElement.innerText += ' ';
    }, 50 * (i * words.length + letters.length));
  }
};
```

This version splits the message into individual words and then splits each word into individual characters. It then iterates through each character, adding it to the `innerText` property using a `setTimeout` function with a delay that takes into account both the word and character indices.

In addition, it checks if the current character is the last character in the last word. If not, it adds a space to the `innerText` property after the word. This should ensure that spaces are included between each word in the message.

